## USER RESEARCH

### Top 5 Pain Points *(sourced from Beautylish, Lemon8, WhoWhatWear, nail tech expert quotes, industry editorial)*

1. **"I don't know if almond will look good on MY hands specifically"** — The universal pre-commitment anxiety. Users have seen it on others and on Instagram but cannot visualise it on their own finger type. Vague content saying "suits most people" does not resolve this.

2. **"I have short or chubby fingers and I'm scared almond will make them look worse"** — The most emotionally loaded question. Multiple editorial sources (Summit Salon Academy, DTK Nail Supply, celebrity manicurist Julie Kandalec via Fashionista) confirm this is one of the most recurring anxieties, with conflicting advice circulating online.

3. **"My nail beds are wide — is almond going to make that more obvious?"** — Wide-nail-bed readers feel excluded from the shape conversation. Celebrity manicurist Jacqueline Pham (via NewBeauty) explicitly states almond on shorter, wider nail beds "may appear stubby or less flattering" — this honest nuance is absent from most ranking posts.

4. **"I don't know how much length I actually need before I can get almond"** — Length ambiguity prevents commitment. Readers ask this constantly (PAA confirmed, Google autocomplete confirmed). Most content says "longer nails are best" without giving a practical minimum.

5. **"I want to try it but I'm not sure if press-ons count or if I need a full salon set"** — Low-commitment testing anxiety. Lemon8 discussions and Ezmio editorial confirm that press-on testing is a growing pre-salon step that readers actively seek validation for before spending money.

### User Sentiment
Anxious and aspirational — they *want* the shape, they're drawn to it, but are held back by lack of confident, specific guidance tailored to their actual hands.

